	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Honestly I don't think those particular SoC clone systems are interesting, nor do I think overclocking/LED mods are. To me overclocking seems like a silly macho fad thing that people should be over by now. I think FDS belt fixing/retuning type stuff would actually be more useful to people who can't read Japanese sites. Here are some projects I would be interested in seeing these projects (if I probably couldn't do them myself):
<br />
<br />-Upgrade FC/NES memory to 8K for dev purposes (just connect most significant A lines)
<br />-Create a hardware debugger/stepper for NES using a save-state mechanism (OK so this one isn't so easy, especially not with discrete logic :)
<br />-Create open HID compliant USB game pad with a microcontroller for people to use with newer more accurate emulators
<br />-RGB -&gt; component transcoder using opamps for MD/PCE/SFC/NG etc
<br />-USB adapted Dreamcast coders cable
<br />-Create a 74 series digital counter and RGB LED based JP/EN &amp; 50/60Hz import mod for MD/SAT using reset or something so they don't have to add ugly toggle switches. Maybe the same for SFC w/ 50/60Hz and CIC.
<br />-Tap digital audio from consoles
<br />-Multi-console power supply
<br />
<br />
<br />Also If I had to do a overclocking mod, I would do a VCO in a PLL with the original oscillator so it's reliable and so people could tune instead of switching between different crystals which seems inelegant.
<br />
<br />I also think most people here would sooner just illegally load up a ROM of a game instead of spending bandwidth seeing it reviewed (or maybe that's just me)
<br />
<br />If you know of any undiscovered, rare and/or expensive SAT/PSX/PS2 games, I would watch those be reviewed though.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


