	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I don't really see the difference between console overclocking and PC overclocking, at least PC overclocking won't bring down software compatibility. As I'm sure you know, lots of FC games use cycle-timed code to generate raster graphics, these of course will not work correctly.
<br />
<br />Some of those suggestions of mine wouldn't be feasible in video form or are they "retro" clearly but I think all of those projects would have great appeal, at least a lot more than overclocking or Famiclones from 2003 onwards. If I had a "mod" site, those are some projects I'd cover is all.
<br />
<br />
<br />I would assume some people here would add RAM to the NES if it was required for the debugger. I think most people here would want a real hardware debugger and build one if plans were out there.
<br />
<br />I think some people here would build a NES pad to use with DirectInput emulators also developed by people here. I think many general ROM kiddies would like to play with real controllers too.
<br />
<br />I think just about every A/Vphile retrogamer would want component video and digital sound from their old consoles.
<br />
<br />I think import gamers who have concerns about devaluing their consoles by case-modding would like the digital switch idea.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Epicenter</b> [ Sun Apr 08, 2007 11:30 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">kyuusaku wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I don't really see the difference between console overclocking and PC overclocking, at least PC overclocking won't bring down software compatibility. As I'm sure you know, lots of FC games use cycle-timed code to generate raster graphics, these of course will not work correctly.</div><br />In my experience, most games are not cycle-timed, they rely on regular interrupts that are unchanged by overclocking the 2A03. There is the potential for it to miss NMI signals but I have not encountered any games that experience serious problems resulting from this. The better games seem to be the ones with the more 'correct' timing algorithms, not just running as fast as is physically possible on the 6502 at ~1.79 MHz. I intend to test many more to see what crops up, and I'm positive I'll see some interesting issues, but likely on an oppressed minority of games. I've only seen any sort of graphical corruption past 3.5 MHz, twice the original speed of the NES/FC's CPU, and beyond the reasonable limit of 'practical' overclocking. ~2.3 MHz is enough to remove most lag entirely.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">kyuusaku wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Some of those suggestions of mine wouldn't be feasible in video form or are they "retro" clearly but I think all of those projects would have great appeal, at least a lot more than overclocking or Famiclones from 2003 onwards. If I had a "mod" site, those are some projects I'd cover is all.</div><br />I too find recent Famiclones less interesting, e.g. ~1995 to 2000's are generally pieces of crap. However more recent ones, even NOAC/FOAC based models have much higher build quality and are generally more professional due to the new legality of FC clones making them less 'underground', and OK to sell in conventional brick and mortar stores in the US, for example. This hasn't been the case in the past so you'd mainly just find weird cheap FC clones by the truckload in places with less/none Nintendo-imposed restriction such as China, Korea, Russia, etc.<br /><br />I still find older clones more interesting. That's why I have planned reviews of very old FC clones from the early 90s and late 80s, many of which use discrete ICs rather than one common 'FOAC/NOAC' ASIC.<br /><br />While your project ideas might be very appealing to people of this forum with an intimate grasp of electronics and NES programming/emulation, as well as for other systems, I have my doubts about their widespread appeal and therefore the value of the time investment. I'm sure you see where I'm coming from, there.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">kyuusaku wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I would assume some people here would add RAM to the NES if it was required for the debugger. I think most people here would want a real hardware debugger and build one if plans were out there.</div><br />I'm not the best person in the world to build a debugger. I'm more of a hacker than an engineer. <img src="./images/smilies/icon_wink.gif" alt=";)" title="Wink" /> My biggest concern with ideas like that, and the RAM expansion, is that your average NES/FC player isn't going to be also writing his own homebrew software that can use extra RAM, or a debugger to necessitate its use. The people who really have use for a debugger are probably qualified to design and build one themselves-- will your average retro gaming enthusiast hop on google or youtube to look for a step by step guide to building a device that either will lend 0 functionality to their raw gaming experience, or a device they're unaware of the function of?<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">kyuusaku wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I think some people here would build a NES pad to use with DirectInput emulators also developed by people here. I think many general ROM kiddies would like to play with real controllers too.</div><br />A curious idea but it has been done and therefore is a bit more conventional than I'd like to cover, really. There are quite a few docs out there about wiring up classic controllers to a PC. Honestly I'm more interested in what can be done with physical hardware rather than emulation, or at least what is atypical and has novelty. Emulation doesn't surprise anyone, or make anyone scratch their head and go, 'Huh.'<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">kyuusaku wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I think just about every A/Vphile retrogamer would want component video and digital sound from their old consoles.</div><br />While you can get away with that on some systems (the MD comes to mind) you're not going to swing it on the NES/FC, since the video is composited inside the PPU. <img src="./images/smilies/icon_sad.gif" alt=":(" title="Sad" /> I like the look of RF/composite personally; it blends the pixels together in a way that can best be described as 'poor man's antialiasing'. A lot of developers, some of whom I've spoken with personally, used the 'imperfections' of NTSC video to turn creative dithering into the simulation of hundreds if not thousands more colors than the system can actually generate. Also, using digital audio output on some systems would degrade some of the natural enhancing qualities of analog audio. The sort of thing your local vinyl enthusiast would complain about perhaps. But to me, the less my systems look and sound like an emulator the better. I didn't grow up with perfect RGB where you can count the pixels that compose Mario's moustache, on a 1080i LCD TV with SPDIF audio connections to a 5.1 surround system. Fucks with the experience to do it now. <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /><br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I think import gamers who have concerns about devaluing their consoles by case-modding would like the digital switch idea.</div>
<br />Probably. But in theory they're already 'devaluing' them by modding them at all. The systems I get are rarely in such pristine condition and have at least a little cosmetic damage, e.g. the natural yellowing of FC/FC2/SNES systems, so I consider it an improvement to add functionality even if you're putting a switch or some LEDs on the unit, if it's done in an elegant fashion.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


