		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Epicenter wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">most games are not cycle-timed</div><br />Except for any NROM/CNROM/U*ROM/A*ROM/S*ROM game that uses raster effects bigger than a single sprite 0 split, or any Famicom Disk System program that reads or writes the disk (including the FDS BIOS).<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">My biggest concern with ideas like that, and the RAM expansion, is that your average NES/FC player isn't going to be also writing his own homebrew software that can use extra RAM, or a debugger to necessitate its use. The people who really have use for a debugger are probably qualified to design and build one themselves</div><br />People on gbadev.org develop GBA and DS software and run it on hardware without having to use a soldering iron. Datel sells a hardware debugger for Nintendo DS, primarily intended for finding cheats for use with its Action Replay DS product.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Also, using digital audio output on some systems would degrade some of the natural enhancing qualities of analog audio. The sort of thing your local vinyl enthusiast would complain about perhaps.</div>
<br />Vinyl "warmth" is three factors, all of which can be approximated by a DSP plug-in: <ol style="list-style-type: decimal"><li>a cut in high frequencies, </li><li>friction noise added to the signal before deemphasis, and </li><li>pops and crackles that remind the subconscious mind of a warm fire. </li></ol>

		

